 centuries. The book benefits from a foreword by Mick Carpenter and will appeal to researchers and students interested in all aspects of the history of nursing and the history of care. The book is also designed to be accessible to practitioners and the general reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPsychiatric nursingxHistoryy19th century. 0aPsychiatric nursing--History--19th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aClass.  aCommunity care.  aExperiences.  aGender.  aGood health and well-being.  aInstitutions.  aLearning disabilities.  aMental health.  aMental illness.  aNurses.1 aBorsay, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorsay, Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChatterton, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDale, Pamela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDouglas, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrington, Val, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Vicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonk, Lee-Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, Oonagh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWelshman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499215640uhttps:/